Republicans declared the tax plan dead on arrival before Tuesday night's speech, even though it won't have a formal unveiling until the president's budget hits their desk on February 2.

'This is not a serious proposal,' Brendan Buck, a spokesman for the House Ways and Means Committee chairman Paul Ryan, told the Washington Post. 

'We lift families up and grow the economy with a simpler, flatter tax code, not big tax increases to pay for more Washington spending.' 

Wisconsin Republican Ryan slammed Obama on Fox News, accusing him of using 'class warfare rhetoric'.

'That's not presidential,' he said.

Virginia Republican Rep. Barbara Comstock told DailyMail.com that Obama's tax proposals will go nowhere.

'I think it's pretty clear that that’s a non-starter, and I think the president knows that,' Comstock said. 

'Those kind of tax increases would just be devastating to the economy. And you know we still have a very fragile economy.'

In a speech to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, also levelled the 'class warfare' charge at the president.

Hatch has set his sights on reforming the tax code in a different way.

Obama's plan 'appears to be more about redistribution,' he said, which 'is unfortunate, because we’re going to need real leadership from the White House – not just liberal talking points – if tax reform is going to be successful.' 

