Mitt Romney, the 2012 Republican presidential nominee and former Massachusetts governor who is weighing up a third run for the White House, slammed the president for 'ignoring the fact that the country has elected a Congress that favors smaller government and lower taxes'.

Romney's main competitor for Republican front-runner status, former Florida governor Jeb Bush, vented on Facebook.

'It’s unfortunate President Obama wants to use the tax code to divide us – instead of proposing reforms to create economic opportunity for every American,' he said.

'We can do better.'  

Former secretary of state Hillary Rodham Clinton, the leading Democrat in line for Obama's job after 2016, tweeted that he had 'pointed way to an economy that works for all. Now we need to step up & deliver for the middle class.'

But Texas Republican Senator Ted Cruz had mockery in mind.

He said on Fox News that Obama's reliance on the expansion of government social programs – and the tax hikes that go with them – was a modern political version of the classic Saturday Night Live sketch that featured actor Christopher Walken demanding 'more cowbell' as a solution to every problem faced by a rock band.

'For President Obama, "More cowbell" is "More taxes, more government; more taxes, more government",' Cruz said.

